com.biomatters.geneious.publicapi.documents

Class DocumentField

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.biomatters.geneious.publicapi.documents.DocumentField
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    GComboBox.DescriptionProvider, XMLSerializable, XMLSerializable.OldVersionCompatible

    public final class DocumentField
extends Object
implements XMLSerializable, XMLSerializable.OldVersionCompatible, GComboBox.DescriptionProvider
    A Document Field describes the properties (but not value) of one data item of a plugin document or one field in a search query.

    (the two are connected since query search fields are built from the set of available fields in documents).

    Those fields are created in PluginDocument.getDisplayableFields() and the field information is used when displaying the document in the main Geneious panel (document table) and in constructing advanced search queries.

    Documents should create fields by using one of the many static helpers such as createStringField(java.lang.String, java.lang.String, java.lang.String, boolean, boolean), createDateField(java.lang.String, java.lang.String, java.lang.String) etc.

    There are various ways to assign field values to a document. One is via a SequenceAnnotationGenerator.AnnotationGeneratorResult which allows an annotation generator to assign field values to a document. If you are not using an annotation generator, and are wanting to set a field value on a document, use AnnotatedPluginDocument.setFieldValue(DocumentField, Object) or if you are wanting to provide a field and value from a PluginDocument implementation use PluginDocument.getDisplayableFields() and PluginDocument.getFieldValue(String)

      • NUMBER_OF_MAPPED_LOCATIONS

        public static final DocumentField NUMBER_OF_MAPPED_LOCATIONS
        SequenceDocuments may have this field to indicate the number of places the read maps to the reference sequence(s). For reads that map just once, this field may be null. For reads that map to multiple locations, there will be multiple copies of the read in the contig
        Since:
        API 4.50 (Geneious 5.5.0)
        See Also:
        HAS_ANY_READS_MAPPED_TO_MULTIPLE_LOCATIONS

      • MAPPING_QUALITY

        public static final DocumentField MAPPING_QUALITY
        SequenceDocuments in a contig may have this field to indicate the confidence that this read is mapped to the correct location. This value Q will be between 0 and 254 inclusive, where the probability of the mapping being incorrect is 10^(-Q/10)
        Since:
        API 4.810 (Geneious 8.1.0)

      • HAS_ANY_READS_MAPPED_TO_MULTIPLE_LOCATIONS

        public static final DocumentField HAS_ANY_READS_MAPPED_TO_MULTIPLE_LOCATIONS
        SequenceAlignmentDocuments may have this field to indicate whether or not any reads in it are mapped to multiple locations. i.e. at least one sequence in the alignment has a value of NUMBER_OF_MAPPED_LOCATIONS greater than 1.

        This field will be present on all alignments created in 6.0 or later, with a value of Boolean.TRUE or Boolean.FALSE.

        Since:
        API 4.600 (Geneious 6.0.0)
        See Also:
        NUMBER_OF_MAPPED_LOCATIONS

      • NUMBER_OF_DIFFERENT_MAPPED_READS

        public static final DocumentField NUMBER_OF_DIFFERENT_MAPPED_READS
        SequenceAlignmentDocuments may have this field to indicate the number of different reads that mapped to the reference sequence. This value may be lower than the number of reads in a contig when either reads have been mapped to multiple locations, or reads have been split into separate pieces for RNA seq introns or structural variants.
        Since:
        API 4.902 (Geneious 9.0.2)

      • toXML

        public org.jdom.Element toXML()
        Description copied from interface: XMLSerializable
        Convert object to a JDOM element. The representation should be complete so that XMLSerializable.fromXML(org.jdom.Element) can completely restore the objects representation.

        It is recommended that the returned element use XMLSerializable.ROOT_ELEMENT_NAME as its name, in which case it must not define an attribute called "type". In this case, fromXML, will be called with an element whose name may differ from the element return from this function. This recommendation allows a more compact representation of the XML can be stored.

        This method generally should not be called directly. Instead, you should usually call XMLSerializer.classToXML(String, XMLSerializable) which calls this method internally.

        PluginDocument implementations of this method may choose to throw an XMLSerializationException, enclosed in a RuntimeException.

        Specified by:
        toXML in interface XMLSerializable
        Returns:
        object encoded as a JDOM element

      • toXML

        public org.jdom.Element toXML(Geneious.MajorVersion majorVersion,
                     ProgressListener progressListener)
        Description copied from interface: XMLSerializable.OldVersionCompatible
        Serializes this class to XML format, potentially to a format readable by an earlier version of Geneious. It is acceptable for the XML to include unnecessary tags that will be ignored by the earlier version. For example if the implementation has only extended the XML since the earlier version, then the XML returned may be identical to the XML returned for the current version.

        See XMLSerializable.toXML() for a more detailed description of what it means to serialize to XML.

        All classes that implement this method must also implement XMLSerializable.toXML() and should delegate back to this method using Geneious.getMajorVersion() and ProgressListener.EMPTY as parameters.

        Specified by:
        toXML in interface XMLSerializable.OldVersionCompatible

This must be a version returned greater or equal to a version returned from getVersionSupport(VersionSupportType.OldestVersionSerializableTo) and must never be greater than the current version (Geneious.getMajorVersion())
        progressListener - for reporting progress and cancelling
        Returns:
        object encoded as a JDOM element

      • fromXML

        public void fromXML(org.jdom.Element element)
             throws XMLSerializationException
        Description copied from interface: XMLSerializable
        Restore the object from the JDOM Element returned by XMLSerializable.toXML().

        This method generally should not be called directly. Instead, you should usually call XMLSerializer.classFromXML(org.jdom.Element) or XMLSerializer.classFromXML(org.jdom.Element, Class) which calls this method internally.

        It is optional to implement this method. Instead of implementing an empty constructor and implementing this method properly, the implementation may instead throw an UnsupportedOperationException and implement a constructor that takes a single Element as a parameter. This allows for cleaner code such as support for final fields in the XMLSerializable class.

        The element parameter should not be modified since it may be reused. If you need a modified version of it, take a copy with Element.clone().

        Specified by:
        fromXML in interface XMLSerializable
        Parameters:

      • isEditable

        public boolean isEditable()
        Returns true if the user is able to edit the value of this field.

        There is a subtle distinction between this and #isNeverEditable(), which determines if a field was generated automatically and hence is never editable. This may return true for some fields that the user can still edit but that they need to be warned about.

        Returns:
        true if the user is able to edit the value of this field
        See Also:
        isNeverEditable()

      • isNeverEditable

        public boolean isNeverEditable()
        returns true if the field should never be editable, because it is one of the standard fields for which the value is auto-generated. False otherwise.

        There is a subtle distinction between this and isEditable(), which determines if the user can edit the field. There are some fields which we do allow the user to edit even though isEditable() is false, although we show them a warning. By contrast, fields for which this returns false are never editable under any circumstances.

        Returns:
        true if the field should never be editable because it is one of the standard fields for which the value is generated
        Since:
        API 4.602 (Geneious 6.0.2)
        See Also:
        isEditable()
